<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[264,1323,1257,1723]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,469,1337,1363]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Recognition.</emphasis>
This species cannot be identified at this time. As clues to its identity we have only the original description and whole body illustration (by 
<bibRefCitation author="Brues, C. T." box="[1054,1193,1377,1403]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="331 - 404" refId="ref33192" refString="Brues, C. T. (1904) A monograph of the North American Phoridae. Transactions of the American Entomological Society. 29, 331 - 404." type="journal article" year="1904">Brues 1904</bibRefCitation>
), the latter of which was later rendered in color (
<bibRefCitation author="Brues, C. T." box="[722,865,1417,1443]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refId="ref33222" refString="Brues, C. T. (1906) Diptera, Family Phoridae. In: P. Wytsman (editor). Genera Insectorum. Volume 44, 21 pp." type="book" year="1906">Brues 1906</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Borgmeier, T." box="[888,1116,1417,1443]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 172" refId="ref32847" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1971 b) Further studies on phorid flies, mainly of the Neotropical Region (Diptera, Phoridae). Studia Entomologica, 14, 1 - 172." type="journal article" year="1971">Borgmeier (1971b)</bibRefCitation>
doubted that the specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[446,555,1457,1483]" name="Paraguay" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
(mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Brues, C. T." box="[739,873,1457,1483]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="436 - 442" refId="ref33254" refString="Brues, C. T. (1911) New Diptera of the family Phoridae from Paraguay. Annales Musei Nationalis Hungarici, 9, 436 - 442." type="journal article" year="1911">Brues 1911</bibRefCitation>
) was the same species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[264,1323,1257,1723]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Based on the original description of this species, in which Brues states that the midtibia has “no bristles except a single apical spur,” 
<bibRefCitation author="Borgmeier, T." box="[898,1124,1537,1563]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 172" refId="ref32847" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1971 b) Further studies on phorid flies, mainly of the Neotropical Region (Diptera, Phoridae). Studia Entomologica, 14, 1 - 172." type="journal article" year="1971">Borgmeier (1971b)</bibRefCitation>
inferred that the female of this species lacks dorsal setal palisades and setae, as does the highly unusual female of 
<taxonomicName box="[391,559,1617,1642]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plaumanni">
<emphasis box="[391,559,1617,1642]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. plaumanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Unfortunately, Brues’s illustration shows at least some dorsal setae present, and Borgmeier pronounced it “incorrect.” Thus, the identity of this species is further confused, and I consider it to be unrecognizable at this time.
</paragraph>
